  "articleSummary": "**Summary**  \nThe article argues that “just adding more engineers” is a fallacy because communication overhead grows quadratically with team size (n (n‑1)/2), quickly eroding any productivity gains. It cites studies from Microsoft, *Accelerate*, and IEEE showing that larger teams suffer higher coordination costs, longer onboarding times (3‑6 months for senior engineers), and more interruptions, all of which delay deadlines rather than accelerate delivery. The piece reinforces Brooks’s Law and uses recurring metaphors—“tattooed formula,” “two‑pizza team,” and “O(n²) growth”—to illustrate why small, autonomous teams (5‑9 people) consistently outperform larger ones, regardless of modern tooling. The tone is a data‑driven rant aimed at engineering managers, VP‑level leaders, and anyone involved in staffing or project planning.",
